title: For Sale:  German Steyr Bnz45 Rare Vk98...Ww2 Last Ditch Nazi Volksturm Rifle...Matching & Original...C&R
postcontent: Here's a very rare German rifle that was manufactured close to the end of the World War Two. Manufactured by Steyr-Daimler-Puch using much forced labor, this is a "VK98". It is a "last ditch" variation of the Mauser K98 service rifle that was intended for issue to the German Volksturm. The Volksturm was a last-line defensive force cobbled together of old men, young boys, and other individuals that had been previously deemed unfit for regular military duty. Armed largely with second rate weapons, their mission was to essentially sacrifice themselves in a last stand in defense of the Third Reich. According to records, there were something in the neighborhood of 9500 of these rifles manufactured. They ran in their own serial number range from approximately 1 to 9460 (this is serial number 7021). They are chambered in the 7.92x57mm (8mm Mauser) German service cartridge and feature a largely standard K98 Mauser action. There were several short-cuts made in order to speed production and lower costs and there is some variation within these modifications. The standard barrel-mounted adjustable rear sight was eliminated and in its place a simple fixed V-notch rear sight set into a dovetail milled into the top of the receiver ring. The front sight was crudely welded in place atop the barrel. The left side of the receiver rail lacks the "Mod.98" marking found on the standard military issue, and the military inspection stamps were never applied. The barrel is the late VK98 "thick" variation...a K98 barrel blank that was left largely unfinished with a very noticeable step in diameter about 5-1/2" from the muzzle. The barrel bores were also characteristically counter-bored at the muzzle, perhaps to eliminate distortion or heat-treatment issues from the welding of the front sight. The bolt is also unique to the VK98. The bolt handle is straight, the bolt body had the guide rail milled away, the gas vent holes are round (not oval), and the rear of the bolt body was V-notched to receive the tip of the cocking piece which eliminated the need for the bolt sleeve detent and spring. The rear of the bolt handle root was stamped with the German Eagle/Swastika test proof. The forend of the stock was made intentionally short, eliminating the need for barrel bands (this gives the rifle a "sporterized" look which is completely correct). The stock was decidedly crude and was roughly shaped from a beech wood blank. It had a milled recess for the "blind" internal magazine which had no floorplate. The recoil lug had hollow ends which served as a replacement for the stock disc and was used for bolt disassembly. A rudimentary wire sling attachment was mounted at the front end and a sling slot milled through the butt. There was no buttplate installed, the rear of the stock was left unprotected. The trigger guard was a simplified piece of stamped steel.This rifle is in very good overall condition and is guaranteed to be an authentic VK98, not one of the fakes. It retains almost all of the original phosphate finish on the barrel and receiver. The serial number is stamped on the left side of the barrel and is correctly matching on the original blued bolt. There is no rust or pitting and there are NO import markings. The stock has been sanded but is guaranteed genuine. It has some non-standard grasping grooves cut into the sides of the forend and there are some natural cracks in the wood from hurried drying (these cracks are no caused by damage or abuse and in no way affect the integrity of the stock). The washer is missing from the sling attachment mount on the right side of the forend. This rifle functions properly although I'm not sure it would be a gun that I'd want to fire (the crudeness does not instill a lot of confidence!). The bore is excellent with bright, sharp rifling. It comes with a dried and somewhat worn leather K98 pattern sling.The VK98 is not a particularly handsome rifle and would have been overlooked by most trophy seeking GI's. Because of the relatively low numbers produced and high attrition, the VK98 is a very scarce rifle today and authentic examples are highly sought after. Without any doubt, this is an interesting piece of history that clearly illustrates the dire straights in which the Germans found themselves as the war drew to a close.Buyer pays $25.00 shipping. Your C&R License is acceptable for transfer if permitted in your area.
